5000|$|The hepatoduodenal {{ligament}} is {{the portion}} of the <b>lesser</b> <b>omentum</b> extending between the porta hepatis of the liver and the superior part of the duodenum.|$|E
50|$|Between {{the layers}} of the <b>lesser</b> <b>omentum,</b> where they are {{attached}} to the stomach, run the right and left gastric arteries, as well as the gastric veins.|$|E
50|$|At {{the right}} {{border of the}} <b>lesser</b> <b>omentum,</b> the two layers are continuous, and form a free margin which {{constitutes}} the anterior boundary of the omental foramen.|$|E
5000|$|Anatomically, the <b>lesser</b> <b>omentum</b> {{is divided}} into ligaments, each {{starting}} with the prefix [...] "hepato" [...] to indicate that it connects to the liver at one end.|$|E
50|$|The {{posterior}} {{layer of}} the coronary ligament is reflected from the lower margin of the bare area and is continuous with the right {{layer of the}} <b>lesser</b> <b>omentum.</b>|$|E
